\f0\fs24 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Sir, here is the 
\f1\b engineering blueprint
\f0\b0  I would actually use if the two priorities are 
\f1\b scalability first
\f0\b0  and 
\f1\b highest achievable accuracy
\f0\b0 , with 
\f1\b 97\'9698% treated as a phased target, not a day-1 promise
\f0\b0 .\
My blunt assessment: 
\f1\b 97\'9698% is realistic for mother-brand presence detection in production only after active learning, strict review gating, and packaging-catalog discipline.
\f0\b0  For 
\f1\b exact SKU recognition plus reliable counting
\f0\b0  from messy field photos, that level is possible only in a narrower operating envelope and usually with human review on low-confidence cases. The underlying reason is that shelf-product recognition is a fine-grained retail CV problem where the strongest pattern remains 
\f1\b class-agnostic detection + crop-level retrieval/recognition + OCR + refinement
\f0\b0 , not whole-image prompting. Multimodal grocery-product research also shows that 
\f1\b image + OCR text
\f0\b0  improves fine-grained recognition over image-only approaches. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.01733?utm_source=chatgpt.com"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 arXiv}})\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa321\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 1) Final target architecture\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Use a 
\f1\b multi-stage CV pipeline
\f0\b0 :\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 Image Ingest \uc0\u8594  Image QA \u8594  Pack Detector \u8594  Crop Normalization \u8594  OCR + Visual Retrieval + Hierarchical Classifier \u8594  VLM Arbitrator on hard cases \u8594  Fusion & Calibration \u8594  Auto-approve or Human Review \u8594  Active Learning \u8594  Scheduled Retraining
\f0\fs24 \
That shape is the right one for both scale and accuracy. The retail-recognition literature explicitly supports 
\f1\b class-agnostic object detection followed by similarity search on cropped items
\f0\b0 , and modern multimodal product-recognition work supports combining 
\f1\b visual evidence with extracted package text
\f0\b0 . ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.01733?utm_source=chatgpt.com"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 arXiv}})\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Critical design rules\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Detector is not the SKU recognizer.
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 The detector finds packs; it should start as class-agnostic or coarse-brand only.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Recognition happens on crops, not full shelves.
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 Full-shelf inference is too noisy for exact SKU work.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 OCR is a core signal, not an optional extra.
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 Fine-grained variants often differ by tiny wording or numerals.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Retrieval is mandatory.
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 You need a canonical SKU catalog and top-k similarity search.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 VLM is the arbitrator, not the main worker.
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 Use Gemini only for hard cases, disagreement resolution, and structured fallback.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Human review is a permanent subsystem.
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 It is what makes 97\'9698% possible operationally.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa321\partightenfactor0

